{
  "exemplar_id": "ex_cauda_equina_screen_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Older retired male school teacher with type 2 diabetes (on insulin) presenting with acute-onset stabbing lower back pain that began yesterday while unloading groceries from his pickup truck. Pain is 2/10 at rest but severe with any movement, bending, or coughing, and radiates as an aching pain down the right leg. He denies trauma, fevers, weight loss, numbness or tingling, or muscle weakness. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and his father had prostate cancer. The doctor has just asked about erectile dysfunction (answered no) and is screening for the final red flag features.",
  "good_next_question": "Any issues with incontinence, like having accidents at all, at night or during the day?",
  "rationale": "This question completes the cauda equina syndrome red-flag screen — the single most important rule-out in any acute back pain presentation with leg radiation, because missing it leads to permanent neurologic deficit and is among the highest-litigation diagnoses in medicine. The cluster being tested is saddle anesthesia, bilateral leg weakness, urinary retention/incontinence, fecal incontinence, and new sexual dysfunction; the doctor has just covered ED and is closing the loop on bladder/bowel function. In a patient with a smoking history and family cancer history, the differential also includes malignancy with epidural compression, which makes definitive negative screening even more important. A positive answer (any new incontinence) is an emergency demanding urgent MRI and neurosurgical consult; a negative answer (the actual answer) allows the encounter to proceed as mechanical/radicular back pain with conservative management. Asking this beats re-exploring pain character because it is the question whose answer most changes immediate disposition.",
  "tags": [
    "back_pain",
    "musculoskeletal",
    "neurologic",
    "red_flag_screening",
    "cauda_equina",
    "decisive_closure",
    "elderly"
  ],
